"before i start praising this game, a couple of points. 1. i currently have zero senior squad injuries (and about 5 in my entire 77 man senior and non-senior squad) 2. i started the game with quite a few high scoring games; but have now reduced this to a series of 2-1s. i cant keep a clean sheet to save my life but im not set up to do so. i dont know if that counteracts some of the other comments. i would also say that the injuries/ big scores seem to be more probable at the start of the season. not sure if its related to you being a new manager and your players just coming back from holiday if you are considering playing the franchise for the first time then ask yourself two questions: 1. do you accept this is a management sim rather than a strategy game? 2. do you have plenty of hours to spend making a sucession of decisions that you dont really know are having an affect. if you answer yes to both of the above and have a love of football, then welcome to your second (and unpaid) career!! fm2015 is put, quite simply, the most complete management sim around, and gives the best opportunity to prove that you really know what youre talking about down the pub and how much better you are than your local teams manager. what really sets this game apart is the intransigence of the match engine - you never really know whether your tactics are going to work, making each and every game unpredictable and exciting. what matters in this game is not what you do in each individual match (ignore the fans, theyre dumb) but how you fare over a whole season. the random variation in the match engine is quite large, but over time it minimises itself. if you can handle losing games you should have won in return for knowing it wont shaft your overall position, then you and fm2015 should get along just fine. where it tends to go wrong is if you just cant accept defeat (or a player injury, it would seem). the game is not perfect. for every great thing, there is a little le. for instance, the match highlights can make your team look fluid and genuinely exciting; but then at times your players can just stand their with the ball as the match engines is obviously deciding what to do next. and how many times do i need to see my free kicks sail over the bar? the user interface is much better than fm2014, but the filters dont always work as you would like them to. the scouting system is intuitive and attractive, but your scouts sometimes say things that arent true. all this les are relatively minor and dont impact on how well you do, but you do sometimes wish that si would game test a bit more. but overall, and this is the most important thing, i love the game. im not sure exactly when this turned from a game into a sim; but this year you will have to deal with financial fair play as well as transfer windows (if there were two things designed to annoy fm players...) if you think ffp is all part of the fun then go out, buy the game, take time with the closed season, dont expect too much in the first dozen games and just enjoy the superiority complex you get from successfully managing a fake team in a computer game. ps. its one of those games where the more you know about it, the more fun youll get. there is tons of stuff out there explaining the tactical side of the game. i would recommend taking the time to read some of it.",68.7
